{{Infobox military person | name = Bey Soo Khiang | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = | death_date = | birth_place = [[Singapore]] | death_place = | allegiance = [[Singapore]] | branch = [[Singapore Armed Forces]] | serviceyears = 1973–2000 | rank = [[Lieutenant-General]] | commands = * Chief of [[Republic of Singapore Air Force|Air Force]] (?–1995) * [[Chief of Defence Force (Singapore)|Chief of Defence Force]] (1995–2000) | awards = | spouse = | laterwork = ''see [[#Post-military career]]'' | signature = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }} {{Chinese name|[[Ma (surname)|Bey]]}} {{Chinese|s=马士强|t=馬士強|p=Mǎ Shìqiáng}}
'''Bey Soo Khiang''' is a Singaporean business executive and former air force general. He was the third [[Chief of Defence Force (Singapore)|Chief of Defence Force]] (CDF) of the [[Singapore Armed Forces]] (SAF) from 1995–2000 and held the rank of [[Lieutenant-General]]. He was also the first CDF to be from the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force|Air Force]]. Before he became the CDF, he served as the Chief of Air Force. After retiring from the SAF in 2000, Bey joined [[Singapore Airlines]] and held high executive positions in the company before leaving in 2011.
==Education== Bey was awarded the [[Singapore Armed Forces Overseas Scholarship]] in 1974. He holds [[Bachelor of Arts]] and [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Master of Arts]] degrees in engineering from the [[University of Cambridge]]. He also completed a [[Master of Public Administration]] degree at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]], and attended the Advanced Management Program at [[Harvard Business School]].<ref name="The Wharton Global Alumni Forum">{{cite web|title=Soo Khiang Bey|url=http://www.whartonjakarta12.com/jakarta12/Speakerdetails.aspx?Id=1369|publisher=The Wharton Global Alumni Forum|accessdate=22 September 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926030745/http://www.whartonjakarta12.com/jakarta12/Speakerdetails.aspx?Id=1369|archivedate=26 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Military career== Bey enlisted in the [[Singapore Armed Forces]] (SAF) in 1973 and served as the Chief of [[Republic of Singapore Air Force|Air Force]] before assuming the post of [[Chief of Defence Force (Singapore)|Chief of Defence Force]] (CDF) on 1 July 1995, replacing [[Ng Jui Ping]].<ref name="Changes to Chief of Defence Force and Chief of Army">{{cite web|title=Changes to Chief of Defence Force and Chief of Army|url=http://www.mindef.gov.sg/content/imindef/press_room/official_releases/nr/2000/jan/22jan00_nr.html#.Uj6OST99kTA|publisher=MINDEF|accessdate=22 September 2013|date=22 January 2000}}</ref><ref name="PACF.SI">{{cite web|title=Ng, Jui Ping|url=http://in.reuters.com/finance/stocks/officerProfile?symbol=PACF.SI&officerId=776805|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref><ref name="Bey Soo Khiang resigns from SIA">{{cite web|title=Bey Soo Khiang resigns from SIA|url=http://www.theedgesingapore.com/the-daily-edge/business/23173-bey-soo-khiang-resigns-from-sia.html|publisher=The Edge Singapore|accessdate=22 September 2013|date=16 November 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012528/http://www.theedgesingapore.com/the-daily-edge/business/23173-bey-soo-khiang-resigns-from-sia.html|archivedate=27 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While serving as the Chief of Defence Force, he was also appointed as a member of the board of directors for [[ST Engineering|Singapore Technologies Engineering and Singapore Airlines Limited]].<ref name="The Wharton Global Alumni Forum" />
Bey retired from the SAF on 1 April 2000 and was succeeded by [[Lim Chuan Poh]] as the CDF.<ref name="Changes to Chief of Defence Force and Chief of Army" />
==Post-military career== After leaving the SAF in 2000, Bey joined [[Singapore Airlines]] (SIA) as Executive Vice President Technical and was promoted to Senior EVP Technical & Human Resources two years later. During his time in SIA, he led the project to introduce the [[Airbus A380]] into SIA and also served in the following positions: Chairman of SIA Cargo Pte Ltd; Chairman of Silkair Pte Ltd; Chairman of Singapore Flying College; Board Director of SIA Engineering Company; Virgin Atlantic Limited; Virgin Atlantic Airways Limited; Virgin Travel Group Limited. He is also an active board member in the [[Sentosa Development Corporation]].<ref name="The Wharton Global Alumni Forum" /> In early 2010, he assumed the post of Senior Executive Vice President for Marketing & Corporate Services. Bey left SIA on 28 February 2011.<ref name="Bey Soo Khiang resigns from SIA" />
Bey was appointed as the Vice-Chairman of [[Royal Golden Eagle|RGE Pte Ltd]] in March 2011.<ref name="The Wharton Global Alumni Forum" />
