{{Infobox person | name = Tariq Krim | image =Tariq Krim.jpg | caption = Tariq Krim in 2007 | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|10|25}} | birth_place = [[Paris]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) --> | death_place = | nationality = French | other_names = | residence = Paris | occupation = Entrepreneur | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Tariq Krim''' (born October 25, 1972, in [[Paris]]) is a French serial entrepreneur, creator of [[Netvibes]] and currently the founder and [[CEO]] of [[Jolicloud]], a personal [[cloud computing|cloud content computing]] platform and Joli OS, a free [[operating system]] based on the Jolicloud platform. In 2008, he was the first French national named by the ''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' as one of the top 35 innovators in the world under the age of 35.<ref name="MIT Technological review">{{cite news|last=Roush|first=Wade|title=2007 Young Innovators Under 35: Tariq Krim|url= https://www.technologyreview.in/TR35/Profile.aspx?Cand=T&TRID=612|work=MIT Technology Review}}</ref> He was appointed Chevalier de l’[[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] (Knight of the French Order of Arts and Letters) by the [[Ministry of Culture (France)|French Minister of Culture]] in 2011.<ref name="Ministère de la Culture">{{cite news|title=Nomination ou promotion dans l'ordre des Arts et des Lettres janvier 2011| url=http://www.culturecommunication.gouv.fr/Ministere/Les-services-rattaches-au-Ministre/Section-des-distinctions-honorifiques/Nomination-ou-promotion-dans-l-ordre-des-Arts-et-des-Lettres-janvier-2011|accessdate=22 February 2011|newspaper=Ministère de la Culture}}</ref>
==Early years== Tariq Krim spent his childhood in the historic area of Paris, [[Le Marais]]. His father was an economist and his mother a teacher. Passionate about computers from an early age (he was given his first computer at 10, and created his first [[Minitel]] server at 12 years old), Krim went on to study physics at the [[University of Paris VII]] and obtained his [[post-graduate degree]] from the [[Ecole Nationale Superieure des Telecommunications]] (ENST).<ref name="Les Echos" group="">{{cite news|last=PAQUETTE|first=EMMANUEL|title=Netvibes ou la liberté donnée à l'internaute créateur |url= http://archives.lesechos.fr/archives/2007/lesechos.fr/11/22/300220474.htm|accessdate=22 November 2007|newspaper=Les Echos}}</ref>
==Career== === Journalism === In 1994, after meeting with [[Jean-Francois Bizot]], Krim became a writer for ''[[Novamag]]'' and wrote articles about cyberculture. He continued his career in journalism for the financial daily ''[[La Tribune]]''. First based in Paris, then in [[California]] (he opened the newspaper's [[Silicon Valley]] branch),<ref name="Le Monde">{{cite news|date = 16 May 2007 |last=Brafman|first =Nathalie | title =Tariq Krim, le nouveau gourou du Web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/technologies/article/2007/05/16/tariq-krim-le-nouveau-gourou-du-web_910806_651865.html|accessdate=17 May 2007| work=Le Monde}}</ref> Krim published numerous articles on the Internet industry, including a piece on digital music distribution two years before [[Napster]] was founded.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}
=== Entrepreneurship ===
In 1999, when the internet was still in its infancy in France, Krim decided that he was done with writing about internet innovation and would just "go and do it".<ref name="The Guardian">{{cite news|last=Katz|first=Ian|title=Netvibes, Tariq Krim|url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2006/nov/04/news.weekendmagazine6|accessdate=4 November 2006|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=4 November 2006}}</ref> That year, he founded what would become L8Rmedia, a consulting and publishing company specializing in digital media. Its first branch was in [[San Francisco]]; he later expanded to [[Paris]].<ref name="Wall Strip Chat (Video)">{{cite news|first=Lindsay|title=Wall Strip Chat Sits Down With Tariq Krim|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x34ul8_wallstrip-chat-tariq-krim_fun?start=13#from=embed|newspaper=Wall Strip Chat}}</ref> Its main online publication, GenerationMP3 (formerly "MPTrois.com"), attracts 1.5 million readers per month.<ref name="Les Echos"/> and pioneered the use of [[Citizen journalism|participatory journalism]] in France.<ref name=SME>{{cite web|title=SME Speakers|url=http://sime.nu/speakers/tariq-krim/|work=SME Speakers}}</ref> It is now a leading publication on [[mp3]] technology.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}
In 2005, Krim created Netvibes with Florent Frémont, a developer friend. The personalized dashboard publishing platform claims over 10 million users worldwide, half of whom are in the [[United States]].<ref name="Les Echos"/>
In 2008, Krim left as the head of the company to create Jolicloud in 2009, co-founded with Romain Huet, the company's [[Chief Technical Officer|CTO]].<ref name="Wishful Thinking">{{cite news|last=Sepúlveda Schulz|first= Rodrigo| title = Interview With Tariq Krim|url=http://www.angelmendez.es/2009/04/16/interview-with-tariq-krim-jolicloud-ceo/|accessdate=16 April 2009|newspaper =Wishful Thinking}}</ref> Their vision is to combine cloud technology with a simple user interface. Krim first developed Joli OS, a free operating system, which enabled users to optimise low-cost devices or recycle older computers. In 2012, Jolicloud launched an [[HTML5]]-based cloud platform.<ref name="Tech Crunch">{{cite news|last=Butcher|first=Mike|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/10/27/jolicloud-pivots-up-organise-your-personal-cloud-life-online/|date=27 October 2011}}</ref> Jolicloud is backed by $4.2 million in [[venture capital]] funding from [[Atomico Ventures]], formed by [[Kazaa]] and [[Skype]] founders [[Niklas Zennström]] and [[Janus Friis]], and Mangrove Capital Partners.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://plugg.eu/program/speakers/p/detail/tariq-krim|accessdate=11 March 2010|newspaper=Plugg|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527062832/http://plugg.eu/program/speakers/p/detail/tariq-krim|archivedate=27 May 2010|df=}}</ref>
== Mentoring == In 2008, Krim co-founded ISAI, "the French tech entrepreneurs' fund", which provides seed capital for web and mobile technology startups.<ref name="isai">{{cite web|title=ISAI|url=http://www.isai.fr/en/home/|website=ISAI|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> ISAI's co-founders are all members of France's digerati: Orianne Garcia, founder of Terrafemina.com; Pierre Kosciusko-Morizet, founder of [[Priceminister|PriceMinister]]; Ouriel Ohayon, founder of TechCrunch France and [[AppsFire]]; [[Geoffroy Roux de Bézieux]], CEO of [[Virgin Mobile]]; and Stéphane Treppoz, Chairman of the Executive Board of [[Sarenza]].<ref name=01Net>{{cite news|last=Chicaud|first=Sandrine|title=Six pointures du Web créent un fonds d'investissement pour les jeunes pousses| url= http://pro.01net.com/editorial/396406/six-pointures-du-web-creent-un-fonds-dinvestissement-pour-les-jeunes-pousses/|accessdate=14 November 2008| newspaper= 01Net}}</ref> This combined effort has helped launch websites such as co-voiturage.fr and InstantLuxe.com. Krim has said that he has a "passion for building highly disruptive new products".<ref name=CNN>{{cite news|last= Schonfeld| first=Erick| url=http://money.cnn.com/2006/09/15/technology/disruptors_netvibes.biz2/index.htm|accessdate=20 September 2006| work=CNNMoney|title=Web users feel the 'vibes'|date=20 September 2006}}</ref>
== Net freedom == As one of the first French journalists equipped to write about online conundrums such as [[copyright infringement]] or [[music piracy]] piracy, Krim became an expert on the digital rights of authors.<ref name="Le Monde"/> He advised [[Adami (union)|Adami]], a French civil society that allocates the rights of performers. In 2004 he published a study called "[[Peer-to-Peer]], an New Business Model for Music", in which he cites another study by the French Directorate of Economic Forecasting and Analysis, which concluded that "no systematic correlation can be made between downloading and the state of the music industry".<ref name="Adami Study">{{cite web|last=Krim|first=Tariq|url=http://www.irma.asso.fr/IMG/pdf/Etude-P2P-Tariq-KRIM-ADAMI.pdf|title=Le Peer to peer: Un otre modele economique pour la musique|work=Study|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>
== Thought leadership == Krim is a speaker at global technology and media conferences and summits. He regularly appears on mainstream media, sometimes as an "expert on the Internet" but mostly as Netvibes' charismatic founder. He is currently acknowledged as one of Europe's industry experts on [[cloud computing]] and the future of the Internet.<ref name="ARCEP Colloque">{{cite web|url=http://www.arcep.fr/uploads/tx_gspublication/actes-colloque-mai-juil2011.pdf|title=Growth, Innovation, Regulation|work=Arcep|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>
In 2008, he was awarded the [[Information Technology]] for Business Creation Prize by [[Telecom ParisTech]] and its engineering association (AIST).<ref name="Paris Tech">{{cite web|url=http://www.telecom-paristech.org/docs/2008101113535_08prixcreateur.pdf|title=Les lauréats Prix du Créateur d'Entreprise - Tariq Krim|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> Krim is one of six French personalities to have been selected as a Young Global Leader (YGL) by the [[World Economic Forum]].<ref name="WEF Young Global Leaders">{{cite web|url=http://www.weforum.org/young-global-leaders/tariq-krim/index.html|title=Tariq Krim: Founder and Chief Executive Officer Jolicloud|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>
Krim served on the [[Conseil national du numérique]] as a vice president from 2013 to 2016.
